From Indian Grinding Rocks we travelled to   Camanche Resevoir, road around the Reservoir then on to Ione.--Jim''s report: --In the late afternoon we returned to Camanche and went to North Shore. Inside the area, we went to an overlook to scope and added PACIFIC LOON. Also on the reservoir were Common Loons, American White Pelicans, Canada Geese, Double-crested Cormorants, and so on. Scoping across to the south shore in Calaveras County, we could see all the same birds adding PACIFIC LOON (2) to that county list as well.

TRIP COMMENTS: This was a continuation of the GBNA trip that began in Mitchell Canyon in the morning.  Our numbers dwindled from about 12 to 5 at the end of the day.  These observations are from two trails out of the west side of Rock City.  The area was not very birdy, and the overcast skies had largely returned (it was sunny while we ate lunch - go figure!).  The highlights included the Osprey - our only legitimate water bird of the day! - and two close encounters with a Coyote (it may have been the same Coyote each time, though the sightings were over an hour apart, as the animal in each case was a nursing female).

LOCALITY: South Fork Kern River Valley--general area
TRIP COMMENTS: Red-eyed Vireo (singing male) - 7:15am in South Fork Wildlife Area - 1st South Fork Valley sighting since Guy McCaskie''s during early July 2000 Western Field Ornithologists 25th Annual Meeting. This species was present annually in the 1990s including at least one pair at the nest one summer and up to five territorial males one summer season (Steve Laymon). Two Yellow-billed Cuckoos at same spot. Two calling, then seen, Brown-crested Flycatchers at known location across riparian forest on north side of the South Fork Wildlife Area. Five Long-eared Owls in small riparian forest patch two miles up Chimney Peak National Backcountry By-way from Hwy. 178 ... five miles east of Onyx. Observers: Bob Barnes, Darrell Barnes, Adele Brown, Maria Garcia, Frank Gibson, Martine Metzenheim, Marya Miller, Bob Showers.

TRIP COMMENTS: New Location for Me

I met John Luther late in the afternoon at Hansen Dam where we birded around the Riparian area close to the Dam. We had a very nice warbler flock that included 2-3 BLACK-THROATED GRAYS, 2 HERMITS, a NASHVILLE, a TOWNSEND'S, several YELLOWS, a WILSON, several COMMON YELLOWTHROATS, YR, & OC WARBLERS. Close to the flock was 2 HAMMOND'S FLYCATCHERS & several ASH-THROATED FLYCATCHERS. We were surprised by the lack of vocalizations! Prior to my arrival John had a vocalizing YELLOW-BREASTED CHAT, BELL'S VIREO & LEAST BITTERN.

Brian Daniels and I returned this morning to Waldo’s Dike at the southern end of Tomales Bay for what was supposed to be a slightly higher tide than that we had the previous day (9:15-11:50 am).  Although the weather was much better, the tide conditions were no better than the previous day, and we again saw relatively few rails.  Note also that almost all of the rails that we saw ended up being taken by the herons.  Today we stood near the middle of the dike, but there were many more people present, so the entire dike seemed to be covered.  Prior to birding the dike, Brian and I spent a short while in Inverness again looking unsuccessfully for the Yellow-crowned Night-Heron (7:45-8:10 am), after which, we went briefly to the National Seashore headquarters (8:15-8:30 am) and then wandered around the Olema Marsh trail (8:30-9:00 am).  The latter trail traversed open, weedy fields and overlooked a small freshwater marsh.  In all, it was a pleasant morning of relatively low-key birding with few highlights.  Also present were Scott and Linda Terrill, Ed Harper and Ed Greaves, Luke Cole, Rich Stallcup, and about 80 others, so it was quite a zoo at the dike.  It was partly cloudy and quite calm, but with a trace breeze from the south coming up later in the morning.  Temperatures were in the upper 40s to the mid-50s.  A high tide of 6.52 feet was predicted at Inverness at 11:19 am.  7:45-11:50 am.----rodent sp. - 1 (we saw one rodent taken by a heron that looked much like a cotton rat, in that it was relatively large, plump, and grayish with a relatively short tail, but I suspect it was probably a vole).

My first serious solo birding of the trip, at Upper Newport Bay.  Clear at first, becoming overcast; high tide.  Highlight was my first Black Skimmers!  The rails were only glimpsed and heard briefly.  Some teals showing light blue wing patches flew by, but I couldn''t distinguish between Blue-winged and Cinnamon.  Short-billed seemed a better match than Long-billed for the dowitchers (nonbreeding plumage), given lighter speckling on the breast and pale centers to the back feathers.  At least 1 of the curlews seemed to show a head (crown) pattern more reminiscent of a Whimbrel, but the bill was still very long.

LOCALITY: Salton Sea--north end (please consider using a more specific location)
TRIP COMMENTS: hot!. Birding with JR, DVP, OJ, etc at  White water river mouth @ Salton Sea looking for the Blue-booted Booby (lifer); then end of Rd 84 for Reddish Egret (DVP & Adam S.); rd ;76 then on to Imperial for the Piping Plover.----Hearing that the Blue-footed Booby that Mike San Miguel and Curtis Marantz found on the 5th was still present on the 6th, Ryan and I drove down to the Salton Sea from Santa Barbara.  We camped near the Whitewater River mouth, and were on-scene before sunrise.  Two pairs of other birders whom I did not recognize joined us, and the six of us scoped the large flock of birds at the River mouth, as well as those cruising about over the Sea itself.  We spent about an hour before I had the Booby plunge-dive through my field of view.  I yelled to Ryan that I had the Booby, and he scoped and photographed it from his position closer to the Seashore.  The bird flew around, harassed by Caspian Terns and performing shallow plunge-dives.  About ten or fifteen minutes after the bird made its first pass by the River mouth, David Vander Pluym, Adam Searcy, Francis Oliver, Jim Rowoth and Oscar Johnson arrived.  Oscar, Francis and Adam were able to obtain quick views, but the bird had flown out of view along the ‘coastline’ before Dave and Jim were able to see it.  They stayed behind, while Oscar, Ryan and I headed to the south end of the Sea (where Oscar eventually found the Piping Plover).

LOCALITY: north end Salton Sea, Whitewater River at Lincoln Street
TRIP COMMENTS: Had also recorded Mew Gull for this checklist, but eBird is indicated it would be rare and I had not noted substantiating information on the identification. Stop was part of return trip to Berkeley from Yuma. Notes for the overall day: Drove from Yuma to Victorville, investigating the ag fields to the south of Salton Sea, then driving around E side of sea and checking out dikes at north end, SW of Mecca. A book told us to drive a dike at south end of Lincoln avenue and go to the water, but the dike had a posting by the Torres Martinez Indian Tribe to stay out. Thus we had to just bird along the drainage ditch and some scrub near the dike. Then we headed north to Big Morongo and took a late afternoon stroll around the dormant cottonwoods and desert scrub. Departed Morongo at 16:40 as the sunset lit up the sky and the temperatures dropped.

LOCALITY: Milagra Ridge--Golden Gate National Recreation Area

TRIP COMMENTS: A beautiful day, mild and sunny.  Peggy and I walked this trail from Millbrae Avenue exit for .5 miles on dirt, then the first mile of the paved trail south of there that goes on the southern edge of San Andreas Lake/Reservoir.  The Osprey was a highlight.  We saw one California Towhee that had a terrible case of the eye disease that has plagued House Finches - it had lost all the feathering around the eyes and on much of the face, and the eyes looked swollen.  We also had a plethora of baby birds being fed by adults - Forster's Terns, Lesser Goldfinch, and Dark-eyed Junco in particular.  Someday we will attempt the full six-mile hike.

Male came out first, black body, white head, red on back of crown; female second, white head with no red, though it did make the yellow around the bill noticeable.  This was a really lucky sighting, with one excellent view of each bird; then they flew off and did not return before we had to push on!

my notes on the location for the Tiaga Flycatcher:--Location: Go west along Hwy 128 from Winters. As you go west on 128 watch the mileage markers on the right side of the road. As you head west on Hwy 128, you will go past Lake Solano Park (which is at the intersection of Hwy 128 and Pleasants Valley Road). Approximately 3 miles past Lake Solano Park/Pleasants Valley Road intersection is the location for the bird. Just west of mile marker 1.32 (along highway 128), there is a turn off to the south (left as you are heading west on hwy 128). This leads to a small dirt parking lot. You can park here or on the highway.----I only saw the bird along the north side of the river (which is where it was generally being seen). I think this was only in Yolo county
